00:01:44.840 --> 00:01:49.220
It's very painful to read.

00:01:49.220 --> 00:01:52.610
So sometimes, I would
actually have to put it aside.

00:01:52.610 --> 00:01:55.460
But it's a story that
needs to be told.

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:58.850
And I think all of
us need to read it.

00:01:58.850 --> 00:02:02.150
It helps to understand
the underpinnings

00:02:02.150 --> 00:02:04.610
of the racial
complexity and the times

00:02:04.610 --> 00:02:06.680
that we are living through now.

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:10.190
So I would encourage
all of you to read it.

00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:14.930
And I want to tell you a bit
about the author, Yaa Gyasi,

00:02:14.930 --> 00:02:18.710
who's going to join us
onstage in a few minutes.

00:02:18.710 --> 00:02:22.490
She is originally from Ghana.

00:02:22.490 --> 00:02:25.040
And she's a Stanford alum.

00:02:25.040 --> 00:02:29.480
And she also graduated
from the Iowa--

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:34.130
it's very esteemed-- the
Iowa Writers' Program.

00:02:34.130 --> 00:02:36.780
So we're honored
to have her here,

00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:39.920
and blessed to have her here.

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:46.490
Her book tells the story of
two sisters, Effia and Esi.

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:51.770
And they grew up during
the 18th century in Ghana,

00:02:51.770 --> 00:02:54.800
and they lived in two
different villages.

00:02:54.800 --> 00:03:00.560
And Effia is married
off to an Englishman

00:03:00.560 --> 00:03:05.780
and lives in a very
palatial castle,

00:03:05.780 --> 00:03:10.370
but right below
her is her sister.

00:03:10.370 --> 00:03:13.430
And her sister
lives in a dungeon,

00:03:13.430 --> 00:03:15.770
right below this castle.

00:03:15.770 --> 00:03:19.190
And it's a women's dungeon.

00:03:19.190 --> 00:03:22.280
Of course, they also
had one for males.

00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:26.090
And she's imprisoned
in this dungeon,

00:03:26.090 --> 00:03:33.410
and is eventually given over to
people that put her on a ship

00:03:33.410 --> 00:03:38.060
and send her off to America
to be sold into slavery.

00:03:38.060 --> 00:03:42.200
And this book, this
beautifully written book,

00:03:42.200 --> 00:03:45.440
tells the story of
these two sisters

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:49.800
and their descendants
over a 300-year period.

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:53.600
So it goes through the
wars in Ghana over slavery.

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:57.830
It then takes us to the war
in America over slavery,

00:03:57.830 --> 00:04:01.430
to the coal mines in
the deep south where

00:04:01.430 --> 00:04:05.360
many of the freeing
slaves had to work,

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:08.900
and then to the great
migration north,

00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:13.550
and to the 20th century
Renaissance in Harlem,

00:04:13.550 --> 00:04:16.829
to the present day.

00:04:16.829 --> 00:04:20.380
And it's an amazing,
amazing journey.

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:23.960
And I think we're still on
that journey, as you know.

00:04:23.960 --> 00:04:27.140
But I would encourage you
all to please read the book,

00:04:27.140 --> 00:04:30.380
because it really
helps give you insight

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:33.410
into what's going
on inside ourselves,

00:04:33.410 --> 00:04:37.480
and inside this country,
and across the world.

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:42.710
Joining Yaa on the stage
will be two Googlers

00:04:42.710 --> 00:04:49.970
who are descendants
of African origin.

00:04:49.970 --> 00:04:52.070
And one is Bash.

00:04:52.070 --> 00:04:56.870
And he shares the
same lineage as Effia.

00:04:56.870 --> 00:05:00.830
And the next one is Kanika.

00:05:00.830 --> 00:05:05.240
And she shares the
lineage of Esi.

00:05:05.240 --> 00:05:08.320
And they will join
Yaa in a conversation.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:12.220
And you're all invited to
participate in the conversation

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:13.400
as well.

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:16.490
So please join me and
welcome them to the stage.

