00:06:02.491 --> 00:06:04.600
YAA GYASI: OK.

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:07.020
SEGUN BASH: Can you give us
a little bit more context

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:07.710
about yourself?

00:06:07.710 --> 00:06:10.126
We know you moved here when
you were little to Huntsville,

00:06:10.126 --> 00:06:13.032
Alabama, but tell us a little
bit about the story of Yaa.

00:06:13.032 --> 00:06:16.320
YAA GYASI: So I was born
in Ghana, in Mampong.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:20.580
And then my family moved
when I was two to America.

00:06:20.580 --> 00:06:23.400
And we first moved
to Ohio, my father

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:27.765
was getting his PhD at
Ohio State, in French.

00:06:27.765 --> 00:06:29.910
And he's a French professor.

00:06:29.910 --> 00:06:32.790
And then kind of as he was
looking for a tenure track job,

00:06:32.790 --> 00:06:34.110
we moved a lot.

00:06:34.110 --> 00:06:37.800
So we lived in Ohio first,
and then Illinois, Tennessee,

00:06:37.800 --> 00:06:38.760
and then Alabama.

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:42.000
And we moved to Alabama
when I was nine.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.460
And I stayed there
until 18, when

00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:46.590
I left to come to Stanford.

00:06:46.590 --> 00:06:51.990
And then, after that, I took
a year off between college

00:06:51.990 --> 00:06:52.920
and grad school.

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:56.070
And I went to graduate school
at the University of Iowa

00:06:56.070 --> 00:06:58.860
at the Writers'
Workshop, which is where

00:06:58.860 --> 00:07:01.447
I wrote most of "Homegoing."

00:07:01.447 --> 00:07:02.280
SEGUN BASH: Amazing.

00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:02.640
KANIKA: Yeah.

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:03.165
SEGUN BASH: Thank you.

00:07:03.165 --> 00:07:04.120
All right, Kanika?

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:07.050
KANIKA: So Yaa,
I'm just thrilled

00:07:07.050 --> 00:07:09.324
to be up here with you,
so thank you again.

00:07:09.324 --> 00:07:09.990
YAA GYASI: Yeah.

00:07:09.990 --> 00:07:11.615
KANIKA: So I think,
between Bash and I,

00:07:11.615 --> 00:07:14.490
we have probably seen every
interview you've done,

00:07:14.490 --> 00:07:17.601
every article written about you,
and read a few of the articles

00:07:17.601 --> 00:07:18.600
you've written yourself.

00:07:18.600 --> 00:07:20.370
And so we know that
you've wanted to be

00:07:20.370 --> 00:07:22.320
a writer since you were young.

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:24.120
We're curious, what is
it that you would be

00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:26.190
doing if you weren't a writer?

00:07:26.190 --> 00:07:27.330
YAA GYASI: Oh, man.

00:07:27.330 --> 00:07:30.120
I don't know what I would be
doing if I weren't a writer.

00:07:30.120 --> 00:07:33.810
I really hadn't thought
of any other career

00:07:33.810 --> 00:07:35.740
that I wanted to do.

00:07:35.740 --> 00:07:38.424
I mean, I sang growing up.

00:07:38.424 --> 00:07:40.590
Actually, one of the people
that I used to sing with

00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:44.110
is in this room, Adam Seaton.

00:07:44.110 --> 00:07:46.260
And so, I think, for a
brief period of time,

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:48.810
I thought that I
wanted to be a singer.

00:07:48.810 --> 00:07:50.904
But that felt
completely unattainable.

00:07:50.904 --> 00:07:52.320
And if you can
believe it, writing

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:56.809
felt like the more stable
career choice to go for.

00:07:56.809 --> 00:07:57.850
So that's what I decided.

00:07:57.850 --> 00:07:59.897
KANIKA: Not the startup
that you worked at?

00:07:59.897 --> 00:08:00.480
YAA GYASI: No.

00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:01.420
KANIKA: No?

00:08:01.420 --> 00:08:03.900
When we saw that,
we were, like, well,

00:08:03.900 --> 00:08:06.627
Google's kind of a startup-ish
with 70,000 people.

00:08:06.627 --> 00:08:07.710
YAA GYASI: Very different.

00:08:07.710 --> 00:08:09.285
KANIKA: Still trying to
preserve that startup culture.

00:08:09.285 --> 00:08:09.570
YAA GYASI: Yeah.

00:08:09.570 --> 00:08:11.486
KANIKA: But I know that
you were at a startup,

00:08:11.486 --> 00:08:13.201
for those of you who don't know.

00:08:13.201 --> 00:08:14.325
Was it right after college?

00:08:14.325 --> 00:08:15.840
YAA GYASI: It was right
after college, yeah.

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:17.760
KANIKA: And it doesn't
sound like that worked out?

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:18.390
Just curious why it
wasn't a good match.

00:08:18.390 --> 00:08:18.973
YAA GYASI: No.

00:08:18.973 --> 00:08:23.280
I went into it knowing that
I was just taking a year off

00:08:23.280 --> 00:08:27.900
between college and
grad school, so I didn't

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:29.765
feel like I was there to stay.

00:08:29.765 --> 00:08:30.390
KANIKA: Got it.

00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:31.973
YAA GYASI: And I
think I only ended up

00:08:31.973 --> 00:08:33.860
being there for eight months.

00:08:33.860 --> 00:08:38.610
And I left and started
working on the writing

00:08:38.610 --> 00:08:41.550
that I would be doing once
I got to graduate school.

00:08:41.550 --> 00:08:42.659
SEGUN BASH: Awesome.

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:46.943
For anyone in the room that's
familiar with African parents,

00:08:46.943 --> 00:08:52.170
singing and writing sound
like very hard sells.

00:08:52.170 --> 00:08:54.283
I think my mom is in here, but--

00:08:54.283 --> 00:08:56.902
I shouldn't say-- it felt like
I had three options growing up.

00:08:56.902 --> 00:08:59.110
I was going to be a doctor,
an engineer, or a lawyer.

00:08:59.110 --> 00:08:59.611
That's it.

00:08:59.611 --> 00:09:00.318
YAA GYASI: Mm-hm.

00:09:00.318 --> 00:09:00.870
Yeah.

00:09:00.870 --> 00:09:03.860
SEGUN BASH: So how did
that go about at home?

00:09:03.860 --> 00:09:07.020
YAA GYASI: It
didn't go over well.

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:10.470
I mean, I have to say, I
guess, my parents encouraged me

00:09:10.470 --> 00:09:13.290
in that my dad's a professor
and he teaches French

00:09:13.290 --> 00:09:15.330
in Francophone
African literature,

00:09:15.330 --> 00:09:18.450
and so books were always in our
house and a part of our lives,

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:21.880
and reading was always
a part of my life.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:25.086
And so that part wasn't really
a surprise to them at all.

00:09:25.086 --> 00:09:26.460
But then, suddenly,
I think, when

00:09:26.460 --> 00:09:28.770
I started to vocalize that
that was what I wanted

00:09:28.770 --> 00:09:31.380
to do with my life was
to become a writer,

00:09:31.380 --> 00:09:34.320
I faced some
resistance, I would say.

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:37.020
And really, I think
freshman year of college

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:39.210
was when it kind
of came to a head.

00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:40.740
I think I was
fighting with my mom,

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:44.160
basically, every day about what
I wanted to do with my life

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:48.375
and what I wanted to
be, which I understand.

00:09:48.375 --> 00:09:52.260
You know, you come to America,
you sacrificed so much,

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:55.350
and you've made this very deep
investment in your children.

00:09:55.350 --> 00:09:59.370
And so if they
tell you that they

00:09:59.370 --> 00:10:02.520
don't think that this path that
you've kind of started them on

00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:04.930
is the one that they
want to go on themselves,

00:10:04.930 --> 00:10:07.800
I think it can be
really scary for them.

00:10:07.800 --> 00:10:12.270
But now they both have amnesia
about that whole period

00:10:12.270 --> 00:10:12.776
in my life.

00:10:12.776 --> 00:10:13.942
SEGUN BASH: Very convenient.

00:10:13.942 --> 00:10:14.934
YAA GYASI: Yeah.

00:10:14.934 --> 00:10:17.650
SEGUN BASH: So what
was the tipping point?

00:10:17.650 --> 00:10:21.150
I think there's a lot of
wonderfully talented folks

00:10:21.150 --> 00:10:24.330
in the room that may be
passionate about writing,

00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:25.750
or singing, or doing something.

00:10:25.750 --> 00:10:27.690
What was the tipping
point to help

00:10:27.690 --> 00:10:35.464
gain that support from family,
stop the fighting, essentially?

00:10:35.464 --> 00:10:36.880
YAA GYASI: It was
really just kind

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:40.250
of saying that there was nothing
else that I wanted to do.

00:10:40.250 --> 00:10:43.900
I think, in part, once
they saw how unhappy I

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:48.850
had been in any other kind
of path, in that startup,

00:10:48.850 --> 00:10:51.640
I think that they realized that
that I was very serious when

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:54.580
I said that this was
what I wanted to do

00:10:54.580 --> 00:10:57.740
and started to kind of take
me seriously at that point.

00:10:57.740 --> 00:11:01.550
But you do have to kind of,
I guess, be willing to say,

00:11:01.550 --> 00:11:03.940
this is a line, and I'm
not going to cross it--

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:09.040
if either of you can come with
me on this journey, or not.

00:11:09.040 --> 00:11:12.490
And that's kind of hard
to do when you're young

00:11:12.490 --> 00:11:14.590
and still kind of feeling
out whether or not

00:11:14.590 --> 00:11:17.230
you can make it in
the world of art,

00:11:17.230 --> 00:11:20.024
which is a difficult, difficult
world to get your feet in.

00:11:20.024 --> 00:11:21.940
SEGUN BASH: To get into--
makes perfect sense.

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:27.070
KANIKA: So to quote someone,
who shall remain nameless, I

00:11:27.070 --> 00:11:31.386
heard someone say, Yaa's
hair's always on fleek.

00:11:31.386 --> 00:11:32.710
And I agree.

00:11:32.710 --> 00:11:33.210
I agree.

00:11:33.210 --> 00:11:34.085
YAA GYASI: Thank you.

00:11:34.085 --> 00:11:35.890
KANIKA: And I was just curious.

00:11:35.890 --> 00:11:38.680
As an African-American woman,
I think we always grapple with,

00:11:38.680 --> 00:11:39.700
how am I going to wear my hair?

00:11:39.700 --> 00:11:40.600
Am I going to wear it straight?

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:41.850
Am I going to wear it natural?

00:11:41.850 --> 00:11:44.710
If I wear it natural, what
am I going to do with it?

00:11:44.710 --> 00:11:47.380
And how are people
going to receive it?

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:50.950
Curious about your inspiration
behind the different

00:11:50.950 --> 00:11:52.120
hairstyles that you have.

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:56.020
YAA GYASI: Oh, I've never
gotten that question before.

00:11:56.020 --> 00:11:59.592
I went natural about
three years ago, I guess.

00:11:59.592 --> 00:12:01.300
And I'm one of those
people who had never

00:12:01.300 --> 00:12:02.560
seen her natural hair.

00:12:02.560 --> 00:12:05.620
My mom slapped a relaxer into
my hair when I was like five,

00:12:05.620 --> 00:12:07.570
and so I didn't even
know I didn't even

00:12:07.570 --> 00:12:11.240
know what my hair looked
like growing out of my head.

00:12:11.240 --> 00:12:14.260
And so I think I was
just in graduate school,

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:17.590
and I felt like I had
the time to figure out

00:12:17.590 --> 00:12:20.360
how to take care of it myself.

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:25.750
And so I just chopped it all off
and started this natural hair

00:12:25.750 --> 00:12:27.350
journey.

00:12:27.350 --> 00:12:29.710
I don't know if I have
inspirations for my hairstyle.

00:12:29.710 --> 00:12:31.420
At this point, I'm
traveling so much

00:12:31.420 --> 00:12:35.890
that it's just whatever is easy,
and fast, and will kind of last

00:12:35.890 --> 00:12:37.130
me a long time.

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:38.960
So I do it about once a week.

00:12:38.960 --> 00:12:42.031
I wash it and twist it out,
and that's all that I do.

00:12:42.031 --> 00:12:43.780
KANIKA: I think we can
all relate to that.

00:12:43.780 --> 00:12:45.760
YAA GYASI: Yeah.

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:47.260
KANIKA: And add on to that.

00:12:47.260 --> 00:12:51.009
Anybody who's been at Google
long enough knows about every--

00:12:51.009 --> 00:12:53.050
maybe every month, there's
an email that goes out

00:12:53.050 --> 00:12:55.730
to the Black Googler
network, BGN, that says, hey,

00:12:55.730 --> 00:12:58.274
I just moved to the Bay Area,
where can I get my hair done?

00:12:58.274 --> 00:12:58.940
YAA GYASI: Yeah.

00:12:58.940 --> 00:12:59.380
Yeah.

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:01.004
KANIKA: So if you
want to share, if you

00:13:01.004 --> 00:13:03.262
have any good spots
in the Bay Area

00:13:03.262 --> 00:13:05.470
that you'd like to recommend
and give a shout-out to,

00:13:05.470 --> 00:13:06.110
we welcome that.

00:13:06.110 --> 00:13:07.570
YAA GYASI: No, I
can't remember where

00:13:07.570 --> 00:13:09.611
I used to get my hair done
when I was in college,

00:13:09.611 --> 00:13:11.920
but I definitely sent
that email a few times.

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:15.530
I think I would even look at
pictures of people whose hair I

00:13:15.530 --> 00:13:18.490
liked on campus,
and then email them

00:13:18.490 --> 00:13:20.805
and ask where they've been
getting their hair done.

00:13:20.805 --> 00:13:24.196
Yeah, it's kind of a
desperate situation out here.

00:13:24.196 --> 00:13:24.840
KANIKA: Yes.

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:25.460
Thanks.

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:26.480
SEGUN BASH: I love
that targeting.

00:13:26.480 --> 00:13:28.110
We need to start
doing that with BGN.

00:13:28.110 --> 00:13:31.360
Gotta get that
list with pictures.

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:36.080
Let's switch gears for a
sec and dive into the book.

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:38.110
Tell us a little bit
about the inspiration,

00:13:38.110 --> 00:13:39.910
where this started.

00:13:39.910 --> 00:13:41.989
You went back home
sophomore year.

00:13:41.989 --> 00:13:43.655
Let's hear a little
bit more about that.

00:13:43.655 --> 00:13:44.321
YAA GYASI: Yeah.

00:13:44.321 --> 00:13:47.260
So when I was at Stanford,
my sophomore year,

00:13:47.260 --> 00:13:51.227
I received a fellowship,
called the Chappell-Lougee.

00:13:51.227 --> 00:13:52.810
And they give it to
sophomore students

00:13:52.810 --> 00:13:57.640
to complete a research or
a creative-based project

00:13:57.640 --> 00:13:59.530
the summer between
sophomore and junior year.

00:13:59.530 --> 00:14:01.600
And I knew that I
wanted to use mine

00:14:01.600 --> 00:14:04.240
in order to research a novel.

00:14:04.240 --> 00:14:06.580
And initially, I'd had a
different idea in mind.

00:14:06.580 --> 00:14:09.070
I thought I wanted to
write a book about a mother

00:14:09.070 --> 00:14:10.270
and her daughter.

00:14:10.270 --> 00:14:13.590
And so I thought it would be
nice to go to my own mother's

00:14:13.590 --> 00:14:19.600
hometown, which is Abakrampa
in the central region of Ghana,

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:21.850
and just kind of see
if anything struck me,

00:14:21.850 --> 00:14:24.490
if any inspiration happened,
which is not the right way

00:14:24.490 --> 00:14:30.410
to approach accepting a large
sum of money to do research.

00:14:30.410 --> 00:14:34.030
But thankfully, a
friend came to visit.

00:14:34.030 --> 00:14:36.400
And we ended up going to
the Cape Coast Castle.

00:14:36.400 --> 00:14:39.730
And it was my first time there,
and kind of my first time

00:14:39.730 --> 00:14:42.760
really interacting
with it in any way.

00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:45.780
I hadn't really thought
about it before.

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:49.409
And it was while at the
castle that I took the tour.

00:14:49.409 --> 00:14:51.700
And it was a really kind of
popular tour at that point,

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:53.680
because Obama's family
had just been there,

00:14:53.680 --> 00:14:55.040
I think, a week before me.

00:14:55.040 --> 00:14:58.862
So a lot of people were kind
of flocking to the castle.

00:14:58.862 --> 00:15:00.820
And the tour guide kind
of just took us around,

00:15:00.820 --> 00:15:03.190
and he started to
talk to us about how

00:15:03.190 --> 00:15:06.460
the British soldiers, who
lived and worked in the castle,

00:15:06.460 --> 00:15:09.370
used to married the local
Ghanaian women, which

00:15:09.370 --> 00:15:12.130
was something I had
never heard before

00:15:12.130 --> 00:15:14.320
and really fascinated me.

00:15:14.320 --> 00:15:16.570
And I wondered about
the lives of those women

00:15:16.570 --> 00:15:19.780
and how they could possibly
kind of be walking around

00:15:19.780 --> 00:15:23.290
free above these captives,
because the next thing

00:15:23.290 --> 00:15:28.722
that the tour guide did was to
take us down into the dungeons.

00:15:28.722 --> 00:15:30.680
And I don't know if they
do this in every tour,

00:15:30.680 --> 00:15:33.460
but they closed the door,
so you can see how dark

00:15:33.460 --> 00:15:34.580
and how small it is.

00:15:34.580 --> 00:15:38.610
And there's just a
little ring of light.

00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:42.010
And so I just was
immediately struck

00:15:42.010 --> 00:15:44.740
by that juxtaposition,
the idea of this upstairs,

00:15:44.740 --> 00:15:46.740
downstairs thing.

00:15:46.740 --> 00:15:48.370
And I knew, immediately,
that I wanted

00:15:48.370 --> 00:15:51.490
to write about that
place in some capacity.

00:15:51.490 --> 00:15:54.130
I didn't exactly know
what it would look like,

00:15:54.130 --> 00:15:56.660
or how long it would take,
or anything like that.

00:15:56.660 --> 00:16:00.220
I just, I think it was maybe the
first time in my writing life

00:16:00.220 --> 00:16:02.950
where I felt anything like
a stroke of inspiration.

00:16:02.950 --> 00:16:06.814
I just knew that I wanted
to write about this place.

00:16:06.814 --> 00:16:07.480
SEGUN BASH: Wow.

00:16:07.480 --> 00:16:08.110
That's powerful.

00:16:08.110 --> 00:16:08.776
YAA GYASI: Yeah.

00:16:08.776 --> 00:16:13.030
KANIKA: So Marian gave us
a lovely setup and overview

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:16.300
of the book, but I want to
dig a little bit deeper.

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:17.960
And set up the context for us.

00:16:17.960 --> 00:16:21.010
Tell us a little bit about
what was going on in history

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:22.566
at the start of the book.

00:16:22.566 --> 00:16:24.800
YAA GYASI: So the book
starts with these two half

00:16:24.800 --> 00:16:27.850
sisters, Effia and Esi.

00:16:27.850 --> 00:16:31.960
Effia is born into
this Fante village.

00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:37.030
And she's kind of the daughter
of a relatively powerful man,

00:16:37.030 --> 00:16:39.310
not an incredibly powerful man.

00:16:39.310 --> 00:16:42.640
But her village chief
decides that their village

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:47.780
is going to become a part of
facilitating the slave trade,

00:16:47.780 --> 00:16:50.230
so they're going to kind
of be a stop on this road

00:16:50.230 --> 00:16:54.760
from the inland to the coast.

00:16:54.760 --> 00:16:57.220
And meanwhile, her
family's also thinking

00:16:57.220 --> 00:17:01.600
about who to marry her to,
because she's coming of age.

00:17:01.600 --> 00:17:06.040
And they ultimately
end up, more or less,

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:10.540
giving her away in this
marriage to the British governor

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:13.750
of the Cape Coast Castle,
which was the kind of seat

00:17:13.750 --> 00:17:18.470
of British colonial power in
Ghana during that time period.

00:17:18.470 --> 00:17:24.020
And so she ends up moving
to the castle, living there,

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:27.190
seems like she has a relatively
good life, loves her husband,

00:17:27.190 --> 00:17:30.940
loves her kid, but
at the same time,

00:17:30.940 --> 00:17:35.290
is somewhat aware of
something very nefarious

00:17:35.290 --> 00:17:40.280
that is happening below
her, which is Esi's story.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:43.300
Esi, the second half
sister is an Asante.

00:17:43.300 --> 00:17:46.810
She's born to a very
powerful warrior who

00:17:46.810 --> 00:17:52.140
lives in the inland area in what
was then called the Gold Coast,

00:17:52.140 --> 00:17:54.030
present day Ghana.

00:17:54.030 --> 00:17:58.240
And her father kind
of has led her village

00:17:58.240 --> 00:18:00.910
into all of these
battles, and they've won.

00:18:00.910 --> 00:18:03.910
And things are
looking up for them,

00:18:03.910 --> 00:18:08.380
until some other rival
ethnic group comes

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:10.330
to kind of pay retribution.

00:18:10.330 --> 00:18:12.850
And in this, a
bunch of her people

00:18:12.850 --> 00:18:16.420
are captured and then
marched down to the coast.

00:18:16.420 --> 00:18:19.620
And she ends up being
sold into slavery.

00:18:19.620 --> 00:18:24.070
And so the novel never tells
you whether they intersected

00:18:24.070 --> 00:18:26.560
at the exact same period,
but you get the sense

00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:32.090
that Effia is living above
her sister at one point.

00:18:32.090 --> 00:18:34.180
And so then you
follow down the line,

00:18:34.180 --> 00:18:37.360
descendant after descendant,
into the present day.

00:18:37.360 --> 00:18:39.535
KANIKA: Are you guys
getting a feel for the book?

00:18:39.535 --> 00:18:40.600
It's amazing.

00:18:40.600 --> 00:18:44.514
And that was just like the
first maybe two chapters, maybe?

00:18:44.514 --> 00:18:46.180
YAA GYASI: Yeah, the
first two chapters.

00:18:46.180 --> 00:18:48.910
KANIKA: And there are 15
chapters, I think, altogether.

00:18:48.910 --> 00:18:52.060
And this book has everything
that you can get elsewhere,

00:18:52.060 --> 00:18:54.080
like all the drama
that you're seeing.

00:18:54.080 --> 00:19:00.100
I mean, it addresses
homosexuality,

00:19:00.100 --> 00:19:05.890
let's see, polygamy, people
cheating on their husbands,

00:19:05.890 --> 00:19:09.790
and being a single
parent, just so much.

00:19:09.790 --> 00:19:13.510
And for me, as a woman,
there were a lot of things

00:19:13.510 --> 00:19:16.690
that I felt impacted
women in particular.

00:19:16.690 --> 00:19:18.370
And so I was just
curious, for you,

00:19:18.370 --> 00:19:19.750
what emotions that
this bring out

00:19:19.750 --> 00:19:22.180
in you in writing this
book, particularly

00:19:22.180 --> 00:19:25.630
as it relates to the
women in the book

00:19:25.630 --> 00:19:27.420
and what they experienced?

00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:29.440
YAA GYASI: I always
knew that I wanted women

00:19:29.440 --> 00:19:31.860
to be very central to the book.

00:19:31.860 --> 00:19:35.770
I mean, women are kind
of central to my life.

00:19:35.770 --> 00:19:39.850
I've heard a writer
say people ask her,

00:19:39.850 --> 00:19:42.790
why are there so many
strong women in your novels?

00:19:42.790 --> 00:19:46.390
And she said, well, I
don't know any weak women.

00:19:46.390 --> 00:19:49.930
And that's kind of how I
feel about that subject.

00:19:49.930 --> 00:19:54.910
This book, because I knew it was
going to be multi-generational,

00:19:54.910 --> 00:19:58.480
I knew that I wanted to start
with women, in particular,

00:19:58.480 --> 00:20:02.687
because my people, the
Akans, are matrilineal.

00:20:02.687 --> 00:20:04.270
And so it felt like
an appropriate way

00:20:04.270 --> 00:20:07.000
of kind of setting
up a family, to start

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:10.990
with this matriarch, the
mother of these two sisters,

00:20:10.990 --> 00:20:13.570
and then just kind of
move down in that way.

00:20:13.570 --> 00:20:16.360
But it is equal in that
half of the chapters

00:20:16.360 --> 00:20:19.960
are narrated by men, and half
of them are narrated by women.

00:20:19.960 --> 00:20:28.530
But I do think that, I guess,
my interests lay with the idea

00:20:28.530 --> 00:20:34.860
that women were oftentimes the
backbones to these families

00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:38.370
and kind of exploring what
that meant as we moved down

00:20:38.370 --> 00:20:39.716
the line.

00:20:39.716 --> 00:20:41.415
KANIKA: I feel
like I'm bogarting.

00:20:41.415 --> 00:20:43.040
Do you have a question
you want to ask?

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:43.280
SEGUN BASH: Yeah.

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:44.550
KANIKA: OK, go for it.

00:20:44.550 --> 00:20:45.910
Thanks, Kanika.

00:20:45.910 --> 00:20:47.340
KANIKA: You're welcome.

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:53.250
SEGUN BASH: I think, for
me, that was a very powerful

00:20:53.250 --> 00:20:56.360
visual, to go through the
first portion you were talking

00:20:56.360 --> 00:20:59.580
about around these
women in these very

00:20:59.580 --> 00:21:01.440
different parts of the castle.

00:21:01.440 --> 00:21:03.510
I feel like if I ever
visit the Cape Coast

00:21:03.510 --> 00:21:06.210
Castle, without giving
away any spoilers,

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:08.910
I might be looking
for something.

00:21:08.910 --> 00:21:15.490
But so much of the book
felt amazingly real.

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:18.815
How did you bring that to life?

00:21:18.815 --> 00:21:22.230
I was Wikipediaing and
Googling as I was doing this.

00:21:22.230 --> 00:21:23.260
Like wait, is that real?

00:21:23.260 --> 00:21:24.730
Is it like really there?

00:21:24.730 --> 00:21:27.720
And these were facts that
you built stories around.

00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:30.310
How did you manage to do that
without being overwhelming,

00:21:30.310 --> 00:21:31.270
as you went through it?

00:21:31.270 --> 00:21:33.144
YAA GYASI: Well, I was
overwhelmed every day,

00:21:33.144 --> 00:21:35.370
so I don't know if I
actually managed to do it

00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:37.179
without being overwhelmed.

00:21:37.179 --> 00:21:38.970
I knew, kind of going
in, that it was going

00:21:38.970 --> 00:21:41.940
to take a lot of research.

00:21:41.940 --> 00:21:44.820
But the way that I
approached it was I

00:21:44.820 --> 00:21:47.737
made a family tree at the
very beginning of the process.

00:21:47.737 --> 00:21:50.070
And it looks a lot like the
one at the front of the book

00:21:50.070 --> 00:21:54.150
now, except mine also had the
dates that each chapter would

00:21:54.150 --> 00:21:58.410
take place in and then something
that was happening politically,

00:21:58.410 --> 00:22:02.020
historically in the background
during each time period.

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:06.150
So for Kojo's chapter, it
was the Fugitive Slave Act.

00:22:06.150 --> 00:22:08.940
For Quey's chapter, it
was the Asentewaa War.

00:22:08.940 --> 00:22:11.700
And that kind of just helped
me figure out a starting point

00:22:11.700 --> 00:22:13.380
for the research.

00:22:13.380 --> 00:22:15.390
And then I would spend
a little bit of time

00:22:15.390 --> 00:22:19.350
researching whatever that thing
was, and then the time period,

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:22.950
and just enough to make me feel
as though I had kind of entered

00:22:22.950 --> 00:22:25.059
the world of the character.

00:22:25.059 --> 00:22:27.600
Because I think, sometimes, when
you read historical fiction,

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:31.350
you start to feel like the book
is just stiff with research.

00:22:31.350 --> 00:22:33.690
And it stops feeling as
though it's about the story.

00:22:33.690 --> 00:22:36.930
And I wanted to always kind
of privilege the story.

00:22:36.930 --> 00:22:39.240
And so I say if I ever
came to this crossroad

00:22:39.240 --> 00:22:42.050
where I had to decide between
something that was true

00:22:42.050 --> 00:22:43.800
and something that was
good for the story,

00:22:43.800 --> 00:22:45.175
I would choose
the thing that was

00:22:45.175 --> 00:22:48.180
good for the story, which
not every writer would

00:22:48.180 --> 00:22:48.990
make that choice.

00:22:48.990 --> 00:22:54.270
But I did want it to be
kind of a pleasure to read,

00:22:54.270 --> 00:22:57.070
for lack of a better
way of putting it.

00:22:57.070 --> 00:22:59.700
So just, I wrote
it chronologically,

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:02.790
just kind of using that
family tree as a guide

00:23:02.790 --> 00:23:06.690
and trying to remember to
focus on character first.

00:23:06.690 --> 00:23:08.610
SEGUN BASH: And that
comes through powerfully

00:23:08.610 --> 00:23:11.490
in the structure of the book.

00:23:11.490 --> 00:23:13.350
While Kanika and I were
preparing for this,

00:23:13.350 --> 00:23:14.308
I cheated a little bit.

00:23:14.308 --> 00:23:16.835
I had the audio book, as
well as the physical book.

00:23:16.835 --> 00:23:18.668
And I was listening to
it, and I was saying,

00:23:18.668 --> 00:23:21.360
oh, you got to check out
Chapter 14 or whatever.

00:23:21.360 --> 00:23:24.050
And she's like, dude, there
are no chapters in this book,

00:23:24.050 --> 00:23:27.150
it's just people's names.

00:23:27.150 --> 00:23:31.050
That was a very ambitious
structural choice.

00:23:31.050 --> 00:23:32.892
Had you seen that before?

00:23:32.892 --> 00:23:34.100
What's the story behind that?

00:23:34.100 --> 00:23:35.310
YAA GYASI: Yeah.

00:23:35.310 --> 00:23:39.300
So the structure came about,
probably, about three years

00:23:39.300 --> 00:23:40.410
into the writing process.

00:23:40.410 --> 00:23:42.810
When I first started
the book in 2009,

00:23:42.810 --> 00:23:45.830
I had a much more traditional
structure in mind.

00:23:45.830 --> 00:23:47.580
I thought that I wanted
to write something

00:23:47.580 --> 00:23:49.380
that would be set
in the present,

00:23:49.380 --> 00:23:52.422
and then just flashback
to 18th century Ghana.

00:23:52.422 --> 00:23:54.630
And so if you've read the
book, kind of the first two

00:23:54.630 --> 00:23:56.213
characters and the
last two characters

00:23:56.213 --> 00:23:58.830
were the ones that I
wanted to focus on.

00:23:58.830 --> 00:24:01.050
But then the longer
I worked on it,

00:24:01.050 --> 00:24:04.170
the more that started
to feel just kind

00:24:04.170 --> 00:24:05.790
of not significant enough.

00:24:05.790 --> 00:24:09.570
I wanted to be able to kind
of watch this throughline,

00:24:09.570 --> 00:24:12.000
be able to watch
things like slavery

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.520
and colonialism shift
really gradually

00:24:14.520 --> 00:24:17.830
over this very long
period of time.

00:24:17.830 --> 00:24:20.910
And so I realized that that
aspect, the aspect of time,

00:24:20.910 --> 00:24:23.440
was the most
important thing to me.

00:24:23.440 --> 00:24:24.990
And in order to
capture that, I felt

00:24:24.990 --> 00:24:27.810
like I needed to be able to
stop in as many generations as

00:24:27.810 --> 00:24:31.850
possible, so that it was clear
to me and to the reader how

00:24:31.850 --> 00:24:33.600
these things came from
those things, which

00:24:33.600 --> 00:24:36.030
came from those things,
which came from those things.

00:24:36.030 --> 00:24:38.580
And so you kind of see this
domino effect of history

00:24:38.580 --> 00:24:39.570
as you move.

00:24:39.570 --> 00:24:41.550
And I didn't think I
could do that if I just

00:24:41.550 --> 00:24:45.540
had a book that was set in
the present and flashed back.

00:24:45.540 --> 00:24:48.750
And I've seen a lot of other
multi-generational novels

00:24:48.750 --> 00:24:50.310
before--

00:24:50.310 --> 00:24:53.340
a lot of which I love--

00:24:53.340 --> 00:24:56.730
but I knew that the particular
challenge of "Homegoing"

00:24:56.730 --> 00:24:59.270
was that I was never
going back in time.

00:24:59.270 --> 00:25:01.860
So I was never returning
to a character.

00:25:01.860 --> 00:25:04.620
Each chapter moves
forward in time.

00:25:04.620 --> 00:25:08.910
And you'll hear bits and
pieces about a character

00:25:08.910 --> 00:25:10.770
through their
descendants, but you never

00:25:10.770 --> 00:25:13.560
have a chapter that
returns to the descendant.

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:16.350
So that aspect of it was
probably the hardest thing

00:25:16.350 --> 00:25:18.900
to figure out how to do.

00:25:18.900 --> 00:25:20.095
SEGUN BASH: Awesome.

