also like that kind of
divide that you talk about,

00:38:26.460 --> 00:38:28.790
but then also knowing
that even further back,

00:38:28.790 --> 00:38:31.740
there's this ancestry
from Western Africa,

00:38:31.740 --> 00:38:32.750
most likely, right?

00:38:32.750 --> 00:38:33.959
YAA GYASI: Right.

00:38:33.959 --> 00:38:36.000
AUDIENCE: But what I also
realize is, growing up,

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:38.520
especially, kind of
just after this weekend

00:38:38.520 --> 00:38:43.230
and after the tragic
shooting of Jordan in Dallas,

00:38:43.230 --> 00:38:47.940
a young boy who was killed
over the weekend, it's for me,

00:38:47.940 --> 00:38:50.340
personally, I just
wonder, there's

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:57.150
so much harm in not seeing the
fact that, at any one point,

00:38:57.150 --> 00:39:04.620
those stories don't appear as
our skin color does, right?

00:39:04.620 --> 00:39:07.010
And so those stories
kind of get erased

00:39:07.010 --> 00:39:08.400
under the guise
of this blackness

00:39:08.400 --> 00:39:11.760
and whatever, stereotypes
people might have of you,

00:39:11.760 --> 00:39:13.800
law enforcement
will have of you.

00:39:13.800 --> 00:39:18.150
But my question is,
what do you think

00:39:18.150 --> 00:39:23.070
is the benefits of these
communities coming together,

00:39:23.070 --> 00:39:23.730
right?

00:39:23.730 --> 00:39:26.430
What powers do you think we
might have in the collective

00:39:26.430 --> 00:39:30.570
by understanding the very
real situation that there

00:39:30.570 --> 00:39:34.840
is in this country, of walking
in America as a black woman,

00:39:34.840 --> 00:39:36.000
as a black man?

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:38.490
And so I'd just love to
hear your dreams for what

00:39:38.490 --> 00:39:40.365
that connection might be.

00:39:40.365 --> 00:39:41.220
YAA GYASI: Yeah.

00:39:41.220 --> 00:39:47.220
I mean, I think, aside from
healing, which I shouldn't

00:39:47.220 --> 00:39:50.370
set that aside, because that's
a really important factor,

00:39:50.370 --> 00:39:53.100
the ability to kind
of heal, but it's

00:39:53.100 --> 00:39:56.520
an opportunity to kind of
protect one another as well.

00:39:56.520 --> 00:39:59.574
What you were saying
really resonated with me.

00:39:59.574 --> 00:40:01.740
In that essay that I wrote
for "The New York Times,"

00:40:01.740 --> 00:40:04.260
I talked about the situation
that my little brother had

00:40:04.260 --> 00:40:07.950
gotten into where he was riding
his bike in our neighborhood

00:40:07.950 --> 00:40:12.480
when we lived in a predominantly
white neighborhood in Alabama,

00:40:12.480 --> 00:40:15.330
and our new neighbors
called the police on him.

00:40:15.330 --> 00:40:18.150
And the police came and
kind of sent him home.

00:40:18.150 --> 00:40:20.490
And you're thinking,
this situation

00:40:20.490 --> 00:40:22.830
could have gone so differently.

00:40:22.830 --> 00:40:28.620
And my little brother can't tell
these police officers that he's

00:40:28.620 --> 00:40:30.420
Ghanaian, he's not black.

00:40:30.420 --> 00:40:33.656
So that kind of position
doesn't work outside when

00:40:33.656 --> 00:40:34.530
you leave your house.

00:40:34.530 --> 00:40:36.240
It doesn't work.

00:40:36.240 --> 00:40:40.380
And so the part of the reason
why this community does need

00:40:40.380 --> 00:40:44.040
to come together is, I think,
for protection, for healing,

00:40:44.040 --> 00:40:46.920
for kind of being able to
stick up for one another

00:40:46.920 --> 00:40:51.060
and kind of put a better
face forward for all of us.

00:40:53.790 --> 00:40:54.975
SEGUN BASH: Awesome.

00:40:54.975 --> 00:40:57.350
AUDIENCE: This is going to be
a bit of a loaded question.

00:40:57.350 --> 00:40:59.720
But you alluded
to earlier people

00:40:59.720 --> 00:41:01.310
reaching back into
the past and seeing

00:41:01.310 --> 00:41:04.130
where they're from and all
that, the experience of getting

00:41:04.130 --> 00:41:05.960
to know oneself
through that avenue.

00:41:05.960 --> 00:41:08.780
But the past itself is
both very fragmented,

00:41:08.780 --> 00:41:13.010
because there's this idea of
romanticizing pre-colonial past

00:41:13.010 --> 00:41:17.089
as if it was some ideal
situation where everyone got

00:41:17.089 --> 00:41:19.130
along, when there was
clearly a lot of infighting

00:41:19.130 --> 00:41:19.820
and migration.

00:41:19.820 --> 00:41:23.540
And that's complicated more so
by the fact that there was very

00:41:23.540 --> 00:41:27.140
few remnants of that time
in place in the world after

00:41:27.140 --> 00:41:29.272
colonialism, because
most people's experience

00:41:29.272 --> 00:41:30.980
of their culture,
especially where it's--

00:41:30.980 --> 00:41:32.730
I know, in southern
Africa, for example--

00:41:32.730 --> 00:41:35.280
come from a lot of the
'60s, '70s, and '80s,

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:37.460
especially into the African
culture, for example.

00:41:37.460 --> 00:41:40.730
So to you, what's the
experience of culture?

00:41:40.730 --> 00:41:44.600
And what is the utility of that
culture in self-identification,

00:41:44.600 --> 00:41:45.745
from your perspective?

00:41:45.745 --> 00:41:48.110
YAA GYASI: I think one
of the big challenges

00:41:48.110 --> 00:41:51.290
for writing "Homegoing,"
particularly for those earlier

00:41:51.290 --> 00:41:55.490
chapters, was just
how little research

00:41:55.490 --> 00:41:58.490
I could get my hands on from the
perspective of the people who

00:41:58.490 --> 00:42:01.640
had been going
through these things.

00:42:01.640 --> 00:42:03.370
All of the accounts
that I was reading--

00:42:03.370 --> 00:42:05.953
there was a really helpful book
called "The Door of No Return"

00:42:05.953 --> 00:42:07.910
by William Sinclair
that took that took you

00:42:07.910 --> 00:42:08.960
through the Cape Coast Castle.

00:42:08.960 --> 00:42:10.376
And it had a chapter
on the women.

00:42:10.376 --> 00:42:12.480
It had a chapter
on the children.

00:42:12.480 --> 00:42:16.310
But what was noticeably
absent was any kind

00:42:16.310 --> 00:42:18.860
of chapter on slavery
and what was happening

00:42:18.860 --> 00:42:20.570
in the bottom of this dungeon.

00:42:20.570 --> 00:42:25.400
And so I think one thing
that we are offered now

00:42:25.400 --> 00:42:29.750
is the opportunity to kind
of develop these voices

00:42:29.750 --> 00:42:30.980
through fiction, for me.

00:42:30.980 --> 00:42:34.940
I can only speak, I
guess, for my own medium.

00:42:34.940 --> 00:42:38.240
But it kind of gave me the
opportunity to lend a voice

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:42.170
and kind of create a
presence in a place that

00:42:42.170 --> 00:42:44.780
had once been absent.

00:42:44.780 --> 00:42:47.000
And I think that, even
though it's fictional,

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:53.300
I think that does kind of help
to re-establish a culture that

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:56.930
has been lost and a culture
that has been erased

00:42:56.930 --> 00:43:04.310
and give an opportunity to see
one way to restore something.

00:43:04.310 --> 00:43:07.190
SEGUN BASH: I think
one of the things

00:43:07.190 --> 00:43:10.640
that brings up for me
and for Kanika and I

00:43:10.640 --> 00:43:13.450
as we went through this
experience together--

00:43:13.450 --> 00:43:16.190
like I was saying, the book was
a little bit of group therapy

00:43:16.190 --> 00:43:20.540
from the two different angles,
but African slave traders

00:43:20.540 --> 00:43:25.200
is something you don't
hear a ton about.

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:28.150
And Kanika, if you
don't mind me sharing,

00:43:28.150 --> 00:43:32.330
she was saying that, as she read
that, there was a lot of anger.

00:43:32.330 --> 00:43:38.080
And she asked me quite candidly,
representing the African side,

00:43:38.080 --> 00:43:40.960
do you feel shame?

00:43:40.960 --> 00:43:43.030
And one of the
questions, I think,

00:43:43.030 --> 00:43:48.740
that bubbles up for me is,
what level of responsibility

00:43:48.740 --> 00:43:51.000
do you feel-- and one the
characters speaks to this,

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:53.220
but I'm just curious-- what
level of responsibility

00:43:53.220 --> 00:43:58.280
do you feel like the African
community should inherit,

00:43:58.280 --> 00:44:03.590
and discuss, and take for
how these stories have played

00:44:03.590 --> 00:44:05.290
through?

00:44:05.290 --> 00:44:08.360
YAA GYASI: I guess, first of
all, just the acknowledgement

00:44:08.360 --> 00:44:13.700
that this happened
is very important.

00:44:13.700 --> 00:44:15.290
It's something that
I'd heard about,

00:44:15.290 --> 00:44:18.080
but people kind of mostly talk
about it in whispers, you know?

00:44:18.080 --> 00:44:20.030
It wasn't something
that I had heard

00:44:20.030 --> 00:44:22.340
people talk about really
explicitly, until I

00:44:22.340 --> 00:44:24.500
went to the Cape Coast Castle.

00:44:24.500 --> 00:44:27.290
And the tour guide wasn't trying
to keep it a secret, you know?

00:44:27.290 --> 00:44:29.210
It wasn't like he was
hiding this information.

00:44:29.210 --> 00:44:31.520
If you take the tour,
they'll talk to you

00:44:31.520 --> 00:44:34.280
about the different roles that
the different ethnic groups

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:36.330
had played in this.

00:44:36.330 --> 00:44:38.930
And yet, I feel like there's
this kind of tendency

00:44:38.930 --> 00:44:44.750
to really bristle if you mention
it among people that I've met.

00:44:44.750 --> 00:44:47.360
And I think that reaction
is the wrong one.

00:44:47.360 --> 00:44:50.300
How can you take responsibility,
if you won't even acknowledge

00:44:50.300 --> 00:44:52.267
that it happened at all?

00:44:52.267 --> 00:44:54.350
And so I think that's kind
of the first thing that

00:44:54.350 --> 00:44:56.290
needs to happen.

00:44:56.290 --> 00:44:57.260
SEGUN BASH: Awesome.

00:44:57.260 --> 00:44:59.582
Thank you.

00:44:59.582 --> 00:45:01.040
AUDIENCE: First of
all, Yaa, I just

00:45:01.040 --> 00:45:03.800
want to thank you for
even writing this book.

00:45:03.800 --> 00:45:05.247
I think it sounds
really exciting,

00:45:05.247 --> 00:45:06.830
and I'm looking
forward to reading it.

00:45:06.830 --> 00:45:08.690
And thank you for
being here today.

00:45:08.690 --> 00:45:11.720
And for the organizers, thank
you for putting this together.

00:45:11.720 --> 00:45:15.620
As a man of African descent
who doesn't know what part

00:45:15.620 --> 00:45:17.480
of the continent
I'm from, I'm really

00:45:17.480 --> 00:45:19.442
excited to learn a little
bit more about that.

00:45:19.442 --> 00:45:21.650
And I have to pay at least
$100 for that opportunity.

00:45:21.650 --> 00:45:24.650
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:24.650 --> 00:45:27.770
My question is, do you have
any ideas or inspiration

00:45:27.770 --> 00:45:31.385
for what your next project
or your next book might be?

00:45:31.385 --> 00:45:35.990
YAA GYASI: Yeah, I'm kind of at
the beginning of a new novel.

00:45:35.990 --> 00:45:38.759
I'm really superstitious about
talking about what I'm working

00:45:38.759 --> 00:45:41.360
on, so I won't get too into it.

00:45:41.360 --> 00:45:43.840
But I think it'll be
set in the present,

00:45:43.840 --> 00:45:45.965
mostly because I don't want
to do as much research.

00:45:45.965 --> 00:45:48.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:48.230 --> 00:45:50.930
And yeah, I've heard
other writers talk

00:45:50.930 --> 00:45:53.780
about how you only really have
three things that you ever

00:45:53.780 --> 00:45:55.400
really write about
in your career,

00:45:55.400 --> 00:45:57.230
and you just kind of
circle those things.

00:45:57.230 --> 00:46:01.250
So I think a lot of the themes
that I'm fascinated with

00:46:01.250 --> 00:46:03.890
and a lot of my obsessions
will continue to appear

00:46:03.890 --> 00:46:06.630
in my work from now on.

00:46:06.630 --> 00:46:08.030
KANIKA: When can we expect it?

00:46:08.030 --> 00:46:11.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:11.300 --> 00:46:11.860
No pressure.

00:46:11.860 --> 00:46:12.210
YAA GYASI: Good question.

00:46:12.210 --> 00:46:13.720
That's a really great question.

00:46:13.720 --> 00:46:16.730
KANIKA: We'll all be eagerly
anticipating the arrival of it.

00:46:16.730 --> 00:46:17.604
YAA GYASI: Thank you.

00:46:17.604 --> 00:46:19.388
KANIKA: Absolutely.

00:46:19.388 --> 00:46:21.920
AUDIENCE: My mother and I
read this book together,

00:46:21.920 --> 00:46:24.720
and we absolutely loved it.

00:46:24.720 --> 00:46:28.100
I was struck by your
imagery of the dominoes

00:46:28.100 --> 00:46:32.030
of the black experience, the
African experience in America.

00:46:32.030 --> 00:46:35.870
And there were so many dominoes,
the passing, the unionization.

00:46:35.870 --> 00:46:37.610
I mean, there's just so much.

00:46:37.610 --> 00:46:41.270
Is there anything that
you wanted to include,

00:46:41.270 --> 00:46:43.700
but you just couldn't, you
couldn't pack it into the book?

00:46:43.700 --> 00:46:47.120
Is there anything or any
additional characters,

00:46:47.120 --> 00:46:50.660
or instances, or
moments in black history

00:46:50.660 --> 00:46:53.930
that you just couldn't fit
in, that didn't make it,

00:46:53.930 --> 00:46:55.436
got cut out?

00:46:55.436 --> 00:46:56.810
YAA GYASI: It
didn't get cut out,

00:46:56.810 --> 00:47:01.460
but the most noticeable absence
and the thing that people often

00:47:01.460 --> 00:47:03.950
talk to me about is that I
don't write about the Civil War

00:47:03.950 --> 00:47:04.580
at all.

00:47:04.580 --> 00:47:08.560
So the Civil War kind of acts
as the division between parts

00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:11.620
one and parts two of the novel.

00:47:11.620 --> 00:47:14.990
And that was mostly
because I felt like it was

00:47:14.990 --> 00:47:18.350
a good kind of halfway mark.

00:47:18.350 --> 00:47:20.990
And I felt like we all
kind of know about it.

00:47:20.990 --> 00:47:23.480
And I also just didn't feel
like I had a good Civil War

00:47:23.480 --> 00:47:26.750
story in me to contribute.

00:47:26.750 --> 00:47:30.050
So that's probably
the biggest thing

00:47:30.050 --> 00:47:34.445
that got left out of the book.

00:47:34.445 --> 00:47:36.810
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:36.810 --> 00:47:38.020
I grew up in Ghana.

00:47:38.020 --> 00:47:39.520
I lived there for 13 years.

00:47:39.520 --> 00:47:42.750
And I went to the
castle when I was 12.

00:47:42.750 --> 00:47:45.510
It didn't really have
much of an impact on me.

00:47:45.510 --> 00:47:48.910
I grew up as a refugee in
Ghana, for that matter.

00:47:48.910 --> 00:47:51.120
But there were
claws on the walls,

00:47:51.120 --> 00:47:54.030
I think the room that you
mentioned, with the circle.

00:47:54.030 --> 00:47:56.100
I still have vivid
memories of that.

00:47:56.100 --> 00:48:00.860
And they said the slaves
were fighting each other,

00:48:00.860 --> 00:48:08.070
eating feces, and scratching the
walls just for air and light.

00:48:08.070 --> 00:48:10.860
So that really kind
of struck me just now.

00:48:10.860 --> 00:48:15.110
But at the same time, I moved
to the US when I was 15.

00:48:15.110 --> 00:48:18.510
And unlike most African
stories that I've heard,

00:48:18.510 --> 00:48:21.720
I was excited to meet
other black people here,

00:48:21.720 --> 00:48:24.050
because I didn't have any clue.

00:48:24.050 --> 00:48:25.800
I just saw the music
videos, and I thought

00:48:25.800 --> 00:48:27.150
they were just cool as hell.

00:48:27.150 --> 00:48:29.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:29.640 --> 00:48:33.540
But my first day of
school, I wore a kente,

00:48:33.540 --> 00:48:37.170
like my kente, my
most prized outfit.

00:48:37.170 --> 00:48:39.000
And I wore sandals.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.510
And I went to school and
got clowned on, right?

00:48:41.510 --> 00:48:44.550
I was the darkest
kid in the school.

00:48:44.550 --> 00:48:46.230
I didn't look like anybody.

00:48:46.230 --> 00:48:47.850
I wasn't cool enough.

00:48:47.850 --> 00:48:50.990
And so growing up,
unconsciously, I

00:48:50.990 --> 00:48:52.530
fought the assimilation, right?

00:48:52.530 --> 00:48:54.840
I sound different
from my family.

00:48:54.840 --> 00:48:56.990
All my family sound
African, I sound like this.

00:48:56.990 --> 00:48:59.640
Some people recognize
that I'm African later.

00:48:59.640 --> 00:49:02.970
And so it's like, what
advice do you have for,

00:49:02.970 --> 00:49:05.130
I guess, the black
community, when

00:49:05.130 --> 00:49:09.040
there are people like myself
looking to learn about them,

00:49:09.040 --> 00:49:15.180
but yet we face this
hostile, negative, and almost

00:49:15.180 --> 00:49:18.060
life-changing experience that
is still affecting me today?

00:49:21.532 --> 00:49:26.480
SEGUN BASH: I think that's
for Kanika, and Yaa, and folks

00:49:26.480 --> 00:49:28.147
that want to speak to it.

00:49:28.147 --> 00:49:29.230
It just got a real, y'all.

00:49:29.230 --> 00:49:31.302
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:31.302 --> 00:49:32.260
SEGUN BASH: [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:32.260 --> 00:49:34.270
KANIKA: I'm going to
let our guest go first.

00:49:34.270 --> 00:49:36.246
SEGUN BASH: Yeah.

00:49:36.246 --> 00:49:37.980
YAA GYASI: That's
a great question.

00:49:37.980 --> 00:49:40.460
I mean, I think
part of the reason

00:49:40.460 --> 00:49:43.430
that I wanted to
write "Homegoing"

00:49:43.430 --> 00:49:46.190
in the first place was
because I had kind of always

00:49:46.190 --> 00:49:50.840
felt this sense of not
being, at least for me,

00:49:50.840 --> 00:49:53.480
not being Ghanaian
enough for Ghanaians

00:49:53.480 --> 00:49:56.840
and not being black enough
for black Americans.

00:49:56.840 --> 00:49:58.520
And where did I stand?

00:49:58.520 --> 00:50:01.815
If I couldn't be either of those
things, what did that make me?

00:50:01.815 --> 00:50:04.190
And I think that was something
that I grappled with a lot

00:50:04.190 --> 00:50:05.240
when I was younger.

00:50:05.240 --> 00:50:07.070
And those questions
about identity,

00:50:07.070 --> 00:50:10.230
both racial identity
and ethnic identity,

00:50:10.230 --> 00:50:12.230
were the ones that
were kind of propelling

00:50:12.230 --> 00:50:15.920
me to think about not the
divisions, but the connections.

00:50:15.920 --> 00:50:18.900
And so this book was an
opportunity for me to do that.

00:50:18.900 --> 00:50:21.860
But I don't know
if that was just

00:50:21.860 --> 00:50:24.500
a personal kind of
therapeutic thing that I did.

00:50:24.500 --> 00:50:30.410
And I don't know how to extend
that out for other people.

00:50:30.410 --> 00:50:31.485
I don't know.

00:50:31.485 --> 00:50:33.860
KANIKA: I think this is going
to sound very prescriptive,

00:50:33.860 --> 00:50:37.880
but I think it's about
education and exposure.

00:50:37.880 --> 00:50:41.810
And clearly, the people who came
across you when you came here,

00:50:41.810 --> 00:50:44.510
they had very limited
exposure and had

00:50:44.510 --> 00:50:48.200
certain preconceived notions
in their heads as to what

00:50:48.200 --> 00:50:50.180
you were wearing,
what you looked like,

00:50:50.180 --> 00:50:53.070
and what that represented,
and what that meant.

00:50:53.070 --> 00:50:57.050
And so I think we, everyone in
this room and beyond this room,

00:50:57.050 --> 00:50:59.570
we need to start
taking opportunities

00:50:59.570 --> 00:51:03.710
wherever we can to
educate those around us,

00:51:03.710 --> 00:51:06.476
to educate those
who come after us,

00:51:06.476 --> 00:51:07.850
those who have
come before us who

00:51:07.850 --> 00:51:10.040
have these preconceived
notions in their heads,

00:51:10.040 --> 00:51:11.480
and expose them.

00:51:11.480 --> 00:51:14.810
And so part of it is what
we're doing right now.

00:51:14.810 --> 00:51:18.080
As I look around the room,
I see many different races

00:51:18.080 --> 00:51:19.050
and cultures.

00:51:19.050 --> 00:51:21.750
And for me, it's about learning.

00:51:21.750 --> 00:51:23.500
And I would presume
that, for many of you,

00:51:23.500 --> 00:51:27.620
it's about learning and creating
more understanding as well.

00:51:27.620 --> 00:51:30.100
YAA GYASI: I think that
